[src:j-wilder-tasker/1921-22-connecticut-aggies-men-s-basketball-team] The **1921–22 Connecticut Aggies men's basketball team** represented Connecticut Agricultural College, now the University of Connecticut, in the 1921–22 collegiate men's basketball season.
[src:j-wilder-tasker/1921-22-connecticut-aggies-men-s-basketball-team] The Aggies completed the season with a 15–4 overall record.
[src:j-wilder-tasker/1921-22-connecticut-aggies-men-s-basketball-team] The Aggies were members of the Athletic League of New England State Colleges, where they ended the season with a 6–1 record.
[src:j-wilder-tasker/1921-22-connecticut-aggies-men-s-basketball-team] The Aggies played their home games at Hawley Armory in Storrs, Connecticut, and were led by first-year head coach J.
[src:j-wilder-tasker/1921-22-ncaa-men-s-basketball-season] The **1921–22 NCAA men's basketball season** began in December 1921, progressed through the regular season and conference tournaments, and concluded in March 1922.
[src:j-wilder-tasker/1921-22-ncaa-men-s-basketball-season] Running with the ball (traveling), previously a personal foul, became merely a violation.
[src:j-wilder-tasker/1921-22-ncaa-men-s-basketball-season] A total of 115 college teams played as major independents.
[src:j-wilder-tasker/1921-22-ncaa-men-s-basketball-season] Beloit (12–0) was undefeated and Niagara (27–4) finished with the most wins.
[src:j-wilder-tasker/1921-22-ncaa-men-s-basketball-season] The practice of selecting a Consensus All-American Team did not begin until the 1928–29 season.
[src:j-wilder-tasker/1921-22-ncaa-men-s-basketball-season] The Helms Athletic Foundation later retroactively selected a list of All-Americans for the 1921–22 season.
[src:j-wilder-tasker/1921-22-ncaa-men-s-basketball-season] A number of teams changed coaches during the season and after it ended.
[src:j-wilder-tasker/1921-college-football-season] The **1921 college football season** had no clear-cut champion, with the *Official NCAA Division I Football Records Book* listing California Golden Bears, Cornell Big Red, Iowa Hawkeyes, Lafayette Leopards, Washington & Jefferson Presidents, and Vanderbilt Commodores as champions.
[src:j-wilder-tasker/1921-college-football-season] Only California, Cornell, Iowa, and Lafayette claim national championships for the 1921 season.
[src:j-wilder-tasker/1921-college-football-season] Andy Smith's Pacific Coast Conference champion "Wonder Team" at California continued on its streak since 1920.
[src:j-wilder-tasker/1921-college-football-season] Eastern power Cornell was coached by Gil Dobie and led by one of the sport's great backfields with George Pfann, Eddie Kaw, Floyd Ramsey, and Charles E.
[src:j-wilder-tasker/1921-college-football-season] Jock Sutherland's Lafayette Maroons were led on the line by Frank Schwab.
[src:j-wilder-tasker/1921-college-football-season] Big Ten champion Iowa upset Notre Dame 10–7.
[src:j-wilder-tasker/1921-college-football-season] 1921 was the last season for the old Southern Intercollegiate Athletic Association.
[src:j-wilder-tasker/1921-college-football-season] Vanderbilt tied co-champion Georgia on an onside kick.
[src:j-wilder-tasker/1921-college-football-season] On October 29, Centre upset Harvard 6–0 in what is widely considered one of the greatest upsets in college football history.
[src:j-wilder-tasker/1921-college-football-season] Overjoyed students painted the "impossible formula" C6H0 (Centre 6, Harvard 0) on everything in sight.
[src:j-wilder-tasker/1921-college-football-season] Georgia Tech also claimed a conference title.
[src:j-wilder-tasker/1921-college-football-season] The 1922 Rose Bowl was fought to a scoreless tie, between California and Washington & Jefferson, in the last Rose Bowl to be played at Tournament Park.
[src:j-wilder-tasker/1921-college-football-season] Washington & Jefferson is the smallest school to ever play in a Rose Bowl.
[src:j-wilder-tasker/1921-college-football-season] A historical highlight of the regular season was the 1921 West Virginia vs.
[src:j-wilder-tasker/1921-college-football-season] Pittsburgh football game, the first college football game to be broadcast live on radio.
[src:j-wilder-tasker/1921-college-football-season] Today, college football on radio is common for nearly every game in every division.
[src:j-wilder-tasker/1921-college-football-season] On October 29, Centre College beat Harvard 6 to 0 in what is widely considered one of the greatest upsets in college football history.
[src:j-wilder-tasker/1921-college-football-season] In the 1922 Rose Bowl, heavily favored California played Washington & Jefferson to a scoreless tie.
[src:j-wilder-tasker/1921-college-football-season] The game holds several distinctions including being the only scoreless contest and the first tie in a Rose Bowl.
[src:j-wilder-tasker/1921-college-football-season] Charles Fremont West of Washington & Jefferson was the first African-American quarterback to play in the Rose Bowl, and Herb Kopf, also of Washington and Jefferson, was the first freshman to play in a Rose Bowl.
[src:j-wilder-tasker/1921-college-football-season] The 1922 Rose Bowl was the last played at Tournament Park.
[src:j-wilder-tasker/1921-college-football-season] Washington & Jefferson College, with only 450 students at the time, was the smallest school to ever play in a Rose Bowl.
[src:j-wilder-tasker/1921-connecticut-aggies-football-team] The **1921 Connecticut Aggies football team** represented Connecticut Agricultural College, now the University of Connecticut, in the 1921 college football season.
[src:j-wilder-tasker/1921-connecticut-aggies-football-team] The Aggies were led by first-year head coach J.
[src:j-wilder-tasker/1921-connecticut-aggies-football-team] Wilder Tasker, and completed the season with a record of 3–2–3.
[src:j-wilder-tasker/1922-23-connecticut-aggies-men-s-basketball-team] The **1922–23 Connecticut Aggies men's basketball team** represented Connecticut Agricultural College, now the University of Connecticut, in the 1922–23 collegiate men's basketball season.
[src:j-wilder-tasker/1922-23-connecticut-aggies-men-s-basketball-team] The Aggies completed the season with an 8–7 overall record.
[src:j-wilder-tasker/1922-23-connecticut-aggies-men-s-basketball-team] The Aggies were members of the Athletic League of New England State Colleges, where they ended the season with a 2–1 record.
[src:j-wilder-tasker/1922-23-connecticut-aggies-men-s-basketball-team] The Aggies played their home games at Hawley Armory in Storrs, Connecticut, and were led by second-year head coach J.
[src:j-wilder-tasker/1922-23-connecticut-aggies-men-s-basketball-team] Wilder Tasker and first-year head coach Roy J.
[src:j-wilder-tasker/1922-college-football-season] The **1922 college football season** had a number of unbeaten and untied teams, and no clear-cut champion, with the *Official NCAA Division I Football Records Book* listing California, Cornell, Iowa, Princeton, and Vanderbilt as national champions.
[src:j-wilder-tasker/1922-college-football-season] California, Cornell, and Princeton were all picked by multiple selectors.
[src:j-wilder-tasker/1922-college-football-season] Bill Roper's Princeton team was dubbed the "team of destiny" by Grantland Rice after defeating Chicago 21–18 in the first game nationally broadcast on radio.
[src:j-wilder-tasker/1922-college-football-season] On the same day, Cal defeated USC at the dedication of Rose Bowl Stadium.
[src:j-wilder-tasker/1922-college-football-season] The Southern Conference would begin its first season of football in 1922.
[src:j-wilder-tasker/1922-college-football-season] Vanderbilt tied with North Carolina and Georgia Tech for the conference championship.
[src:j-wilder-tasker/1922-college-football-season] The Commodores tied Michigan 0–0 on October 14 at the dedication of Dudley Field, the South's first permanent college football stadium.
[src:j-wilder-tasker/1922-college-football-season] On the same day, Big Ten champion Iowa upset Yale.
[src:j-wilder-tasker/1922-college-football-season] The 1923 Rose Bowl at season's end was the first called the "Rose Bowl" and was held in the newly constructed stadium.
[src:j-wilder-tasker/1922-college-football-season] In the first bowl appearance for either team, USC beat Penn State 14–3.
[src:j-wilder-tasker/1922-college-football-season] The West Virginia Mountaineers played the Gonzaga Bulldogs in the only other bowl game this season, the San Diego East-West Christmas Classic.
[src:j-wilder-tasker/1922-college-football-season] The 1922 season included the new "try for a point" rule.
[src:j-wilder-tasker/1922-college-football-season] One was allowed to either kick an extra point after a touchdown as usual, or to place the ball anywhere beyond the five yard line and try to score either by touchdown or by a kick, and receive the one point if successful.
[src:j-wilder-tasker/1922-college-football-season] In Nashville, Michigan and Vanderbilt played to a 0–0 tie at the inaugural game for Dudley Field, the first dedicated football-only stadium in the South in the style of the Eastern schools.
[src:j-wilder-tasker/1922-college-football-season] After beating Duke 20–0 in a Thursday game, North Carolina beat South Carolina, 10–7.
[src:j-wilder-tasker/1922-college-football-season] Centre gave VPI its only loss of the season.
[src:j-wilder-tasker/1922-college-football-season] In Dallas, Vanderbilt and Texas, both unbeaten, met at the State Fair, with the Commodores winning 20–10.
[src:j-wilder-tasker/1922-college-football-season] Iowa won at Illinois 8–7, and Michigan won at Ohio State 19–0; In St.
[src:j-wilder-tasker/1922-college-football-season] Louis, Drake beat Washington University, 31–7 Baylor beat Arkansas 60–13 California shut out the Olympic Club team, 25–0.
[src:j-wilder-tasker/1922-college-football-season] California was 4–0–0, and USC was 5–0–0, when the teams met in Pasadena.
[src:j-wilder-tasker/1922-college-football-season] Cal had a 2–0 lead at halftime, and held off USC on two goal line stands, before scoring a touchdown and a field goal to win 12–0.
[src:j-wilder-tasker/1922-college-football-season] The Alabama Crimson Tide had its first intersectional victory, 9–6 over John Heisman's Penn.
[src:j-wilder-tasker/1922-college-football-season] Scott resigned due to cancer at year's end.
[src:j-wilder-tasker/1922-college-football-season] In New Orleans, North Carolina defeated Tulane 19–12.
[src:j-wilder-tasker/1922-college-football-season] Michigan beat Michigan State 63–0, having outscored its opponents 154–0 in its first five games.
[src:j-wilder-tasker/1922-college-football-season] California defeated Washington State, 61–0.
[src:j-wilder-tasker/1922-college-football-season] At the Polo Grounds, Cornell beat Dartmouth, with the Big Red overcoming the Big Green, 23–0.
[src:j-wilder-tasker/1922-college-football-season] In Boston, Baylor lost to Boston College, 33–0.
[src:j-wilder-tasker/1922-college-football-season] In Seattle, California (7–0–0) faced Washington (5–0–0) in a battle of unbeatens, and handed the Huskies their first defeat, 45–7.
[src:j-wilder-tasker/1922-college-football-season] Iowa beat Minnesota 28–14, and Michigan beat Wisconsin 13–6; Drake beat Colorado State, 19–6 Vanderbilt beat Kentucky 9–0 North Carolina beat VMI 9–7 at Richmond.
[src:j-wilder-tasker/1922-college-football-season] In the 1923 Rose Bowl, USC defeated Penn State, 14–3.
[src:j-wilder-tasker/1922-college-football-season] Though USC had an overall record of 9–1 coming into the game, the Trojans finished fourth place in Pacific Coast Conference (PCC) play, behind California, Oregon, and Washington, having been defeated by PCC champion California.
[src:j-wilder-tasker/1922-college-football-season] Penn State won its first five games, then only one of the next five, and had a 6–4–1 record at season's end.
[src:j-wilder-tasker/1922-college-football-season] The 1922 San Diego East-West Christmas Classic was played on December 25 at Balboa Stadium in San Diego, California.
[src:j-wilder-tasker/1922-college-football-season] The West Virginia Mountaineers defeated the Gonzaga Bulldogs, 21 to 13, to finish the season undefeated with a 10–0—1 record.
[src:j-wilder-tasker/1922-college-football-season] Three different "retro polls", taken years later and based on opinions drawn from historical research, reached different conclusions.
[src:j-wilder-tasker/1922-college-football-season] The Helms Athletic Foundation, founded in 1936, declared retroactively that Cornell (8–0) was the best, while the College Football Researchers Association (CFRA) recognized Princeton (8–0), and the National Championship Foundation (NCF) cited California (9–0) and Princeton as best.
[src:j-wilder-tasker/1922-college-football-season] The Princeton team was dubbed the "team of destiny" by Grantland Rice after defeating Chicago in the first game nationally broadcast on radio.
[src:j-wilder-tasker/1922-college-football-season] The other unbeaten and untied team was Iowa (7–0), which canceled its game with unbeaten Drake that year.
[src:j-wilder-tasker/1922-college-football-season] Clyde Berryman retroactively selected Vanderbilt, which tied Michigan, as a national champion.
[src:j-wilder-tasker/1922-connecticut-aggies-football-team] The **1922 Connecticut Aggies football team** represented Connecticut Agricultural College, now the University of Connecticut, in the 1922 college football season.
[src:j-wilder-tasker/1922-connecticut-aggies-football-team] The Aggies were led by second-year head coach J.
[src:j-wilder-tasker/1922-connecticut-aggies-football-team] Wilder Tasker, and completed the season with a record of 2–6–1.
[src:j-wilder-tasker/j-wilder-tasker] Tasker became athletic coach at Connecticut Agricultural College—now known as the University of Connecticut—in 1921.
[src:j-wilder-tasker/j-wilder-tasker] He resigned as coach at Connecticut in January 1923.
[src:j-wilder-tasker/j-wilder-tasker] Guyer, took over coaching of the Connecticut Aggies men's basketball team.
[src:j-wilder-tasker/j-wilder-tasker] In March 1923, Tasker was hired at athletic director and coach at the College of William & Mary in Williamsburg, Virginia.
[src:j-wilder-tasker/j-wilder-tasker] After leaving from coaching, Tasker ran an insurance business in Orange, New Jersey.
[src:j-wilder-tasker/j-wilder-tasker] He retired in the 1960s and moved to Kilmarnock, Virginia, where he died at his home on March 14, 1974.
